♪ With pockets of light ♪

57:29.667 --> 57:36.041
♪ Chasing ♪

57:36.125 --> 57:39.250
♪ The night ♪

58:08.250 --> 58:09.875
OFFICER:
Kenny McMenamin's daughter.

58:10.083 --> 58:11.583
MARE SHEEHAN:
She's been here a while.

58:12.458 --> 58:14.125
♪ (DRAMATIC MUSIC PLAYS) ♪

58:14.208 --> 58:16.000
We need you to remember
as much as you can.

58:16.083 --> 58:17.250
We can find out who did this.

58:17.542 --> 58:19.792
No one else had any reason
to hurt her, 'cept him.

58:20.792 --> 58:22.458
MARE: You got something
you wanna tell me,

58:23.083 --> 58:24.083
you better do it now.

58:24.166 --> 58:25.750
LORI ROSS:
Your family's worried about you.

58:25.959 --> 58:27.125
MARE:
My life's a shitshow.

58:27.542 --> 58:29.375
Sorry if I'm not the life
of the party.

58:29.458 --> 58:31.500
You were never
the life of the party.

58:33.625 --> 58:37.750
Anonymous caller on the tip line
asking us to look into
Deacon Mark's transfer.

58:38.458 --> 58:40.166
-I'm talking to you.
-(GROANS)

58:40.917 --> 58:42.250
SPEAKER:
Erin told me a secret.

58:42.875 --> 58:45.458
And she made me promise
never to tell anyone.

58:47.125 --> 58:49.125
MARE: You know what it's like
when a case gets inside you

58:49.208 --> 58:50.875
-like that?
-You take it home.

58:51.375 --> 58:52.792
Become consumed with it.

58:52.875 --> 58:55.000
Obsessed.
It's all that matters.

58:55.083 --> 58:56.083
I need you to back away.

58:56.458 --> 58:58.375
You're carrying a lot
of heavy stuff.

58:58.792 --> 59:01.166
I wonder if anybody ever
does anything for you.

59:02.041 --> 59:03.166
MARE: First Katie Bailey.

59:03.625 --> 59:05.125
Now, Erin McMenamin.

59:06.250 --> 59:07.667
GAYLE GRAHAM:
And what are you looking for?

59:08.291 --> 59:09.542
Hope, I guess.

59:11.000 --> 59:12.709
The ground is just falling out
beneath you.

59:12.792 --> 59:13.875
We don't know
what's gonna happen.

59:13.959 --> 59:15.458
He's my son, goddammit.

59:15.667 --> 59:17.041
I swear to you,
I didn't kill her.

59:17.125 --> 59:18.125
Shh. Drive.

59:18.750 --> 59:20.375
I know what you've been through.

59:20.458 --> 59:21.333
(SOBBING)

59:21.500 --> 59:23.166
CHIEF CARTER:
I know you're worth saving.

59:25.083 --> 59:26.166
MARE: Put the gun down!

59:26.834 --> 59:27.875
(GUNSHOTS)

59:29.542 --> 59:31.000
I'm gonna find out everything.

59:37.166 --> 59:38.542
♪ (SOMBER MUSIC PLAYS) ♪

59:40.750 --> 59:43.000
(CROWS CAW)

59:45.542 --> 59:49.041
Easttown is a mixture
of a number of different towns

59:49.125 --> 59:51.792
in Pennsylvania
around where I grew up,

59:52.000 --> 59:53.875
and I wanted the show
to be about

59:53.959 --> 59:56.875
a certain place in the world,
a certain group of people.

59:57.291 --> 59:59.083
These people
have been born here.

59:59.291 --> 1:00:00.458
They've been raised here,

1:00:00.709 --> 1:00:03.041
and now they're raising
their children here.

1:00:04.792 --> 1:00:07.208
KATE WINSLET: That sense
of history and shared history,

1:00:07.291 --> 1:00:10.166
united history
that is very apparent

1:00:10.250 --> 1:00:12.625
in this particular area
of Easttown

1:00:12.709 --> 1:00:14.583
is quite unique I would say,

1:00:14.667 --> 1:00:16.917
and-- and everyone knows
a little bit

1:00:17.000 --> 1:00:18.709
about what
someone else is up to,

1:00:18.792 --> 1:00:20.375
and there's always the sort of

1:00:20.458 --> 1:00:22.917
resident, slightly annoying
character

1:00:23.000 --> 1:00:24.250
Mare would have to deal with.

1:00:24.333 --> 1:00:26.250
SPEAKER:
Mare? Mare, you out there?

1:00:28.125 --> 1:00:29.417
Oh, you're here.

1:00:29.500 --> 1:00:30.500
I'm here.

1:00:30.917 --> 1:00:32.291
CRAIG ZOBEL: We shot primarily

1:00:32.375 --> 1:00:34.750
in what I would call
an exurb of Philadelphia,

1:00:34.834 --> 1:00:36.959
kind of like
the southwestern area

1:00:37.041 --> 1:00:39.625
outside Chester County
and Delaware County,

1:00:39.709 --> 1:00:41.917
and that really did inform
so much.

1:00:42.583 --> 1:00:44.917
It was nice to kind of be
in a place

1:00:45.000 --> 1:00:46.667
that felt like America,

1:00:46.750 --> 1:00:48.917
and wasn't so specifically
a big city.

1:00:49.250 --> 1:00:51.875
We wanted to make sure
that the vibe of the show

1:00:51.959 --> 1:00:53.583
and the feeling of Easttown

1:00:53.667 --> 1:00:55.709
was specific
in many different ways.

1:00:55.792 --> 1:00:58.917
We did it through location.
We would try to pick a location

1:00:59.000 --> 1:01:01.333
that was true to what
it really was

1:01:01.417 --> 1:01:03.250
and not just
the most picturesque.

1:01:03.750 --> 1:01:05.583
(HORN HONKS)

1:01:07.375 --> 1:01:08.792
We would do it with costume.

1:01:09.041 --> 1:01:11.375
Our costume designer
would constantly be texting me

1:01:11.458 --> 1:01:13.583
pictures
from the Wawa convenience store,

1:01:13.667 --> 1:01:15.417
just of people in the line.

1:01:15.750 --> 1:01:18.709
JULIANNE NICHOLSON:
The clothes really all felt
lived in to me

1:01:18.792 --> 1:01:20.875
and of that place.
For instance,

1:01:20.959 --> 1:01:24.125
I mean, I had, I think,
a Dave Matthews concert T-shirt

1:01:24.208 --> 1:01:27.375
and certain things that maybe
you won't even see on camera,

1:01:27.458 --> 1:01:29.208
but those little details
for her

1:01:29.291 --> 1:01:31.750
and the actors are important.

1:01:33.166 --> 1:01:35.500
I wanted the show to have
a grittiness to it

1:01:35.583 --> 1:01:38.625
and have an honesty to it,
to have a realness to it.

1:01:39.417 --> 1:01:41.125
These are people that get up
every morning

1:01:41.208 --> 1:01:43.750
and go to jobs that don't
necessarily love,

1:01:43.834 --> 1:01:46.542
but yeah, they do it
out of a sense of duty.

1:01:47.000 --> 1:01:49.667
So, I wanted to portray
these communities that exist

1:01:49.750 --> 1:01:52.458
that don't often get any time
on the screen in a way

1:01:52.542 --> 1:01:55.542
that was heroic and noble
and also really sympathetic.

1:01:55.625 --> 1:01:57.583
MARE SHEEHAN: We're asking
parents if their child

1:01:57.667 --> 1:02:00.041
might have seen something'.
Please come forward.

1:02:00.959 --> 1:02:03.208
Every bit of information
helps at this point.

1:02:04.500 --> 1:02:06.083
GUY PEARCE: What's beautiful
about this story

1:02:06.166 --> 1:02:07.417
is that it isn't
just about the crime,

1:02:07.500 --> 1:02:09.500
it isn't just about the mystery
and who's done it,

1:02:10.000 --> 1:02:11.291
but it's about the families.

1:02:11.667 --> 1:02:13.750
You have the opportunity
to sort of investigate

1:02:13.834 --> 1:02:15.667
all the families
and see the effects

1:02:15.750 --> 1:02:17.500
that the crime has had
and get involved

1:02:17.583 --> 1:02:20.667
in everybody's personal stories
and see how they're interwoven.

1:02:21.917 --> 1:02:24.625
So, there's something
kind of heightened, you know,

1:02:24.709 --> 1:02:27.333
in the drama, I suppose,
when it is a small town.

1:02:27.917 --> 1:02:29.500
You're pushin' everyone away.

1:02:32.333 --> 1:02:33.375
Including you?

1:02:33.709 --> 1:02:35.166
No, I won't let you.

1:02:36.792 --> 1:02:40.333
WINSLET: The show is very much
about compassion and mercy

1:02:40.417 --> 1:02:43.458
and looking out for your friends
and your neighbors,

1:02:43.542 --> 1:02:45.458
and it's quite special
in that regard,

1:02:45.542 --> 1:02:47.208
very moving in that regard.
